When working with Oracle databases, you can check the logging status of a table by using the following steps: 

1) To determine whether a table is in NOLOGGING mode, you can query the DBA_TABLES view as follows: SELECT LOGGING FROM DBA_TABLES WHERE TABLE_NAME = '<table_name>'; 

The LOGGING column would report YES if the table logs all the changes and NO if it was created with the NOLOGGING clause. 

2) Similarly, you can use the dbms_metadata.get_ddl function to extract the DDL for a table, which will display if the table was created with the NOLOGGING option. Example: SELECT dbms_metadata.get_ddl('TABLE','<table_name>') FROM DUAL; 

Please note that the ALTER TABLE command can modify a table to become a NOLOGGING table, but this change will not be reflected in the DDL extracted using the dbms_metadata.get_ddl function. 

